--- PDF SUMMARY (Document was 27 pages long) ---
The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

This study aimed to assess the psychological impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on university students in Jordan, utilizing the Kessler Psychological Distress Scale (K10). A cross-sectional design was adopted, with data collected via an internet-based self-administered questionnaire focusing on sociodemographic information, psychological distress, coping activities, and primary concerns during the pandemic. Social media platforms like Facebook and WhatsApp were used to disseminate the survey among university students across various Jordanian institutions.

A total of 381 students participated, with the sample predominantly female (52.2%). The average participant age was 22.6 years. K10 scores indicated severe psychological distress in the majority (69.5%). Although no significant gender differences were found in total distress scores, females exhibited higher rates of both mild and severe distress. Age inversely correlated with distress scores (P=0.0013). The study highlighted a lack of motivation for distance learning among 54.9% of respondents, revealing a significant inverse relationship between severe distress and learning motivation (P<0.0001).

The most common coping mechanism was increased social media use (70.6%), and 12.9% resorted to medication for distress. The primary concern was adapting to distance learning (54.9%). The findings underscore the substantial mental health impact on students due to COVID-19 and advocate incorporating a psychological support program into Jordan’s response strategies, particularly for students and vulnerable groups.

The study assessed psychological distress using the 10-item Kessler Psychological Distress Scale (K10), which showed strong reliability with a Cronbach’s α of 0.88. The survey included 397 respondents, with only 381 included in the final analysis due to completeness criteria, 
